INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (73,1,'2022-10-09 13:32:51','2022-10-09 13:32:51','','Limpieza_Auditorias_publicadas_2015-2020_sitioCGR','','inherit','open','closed','','limpieza_auditorias_publicadas_2015-2020_sitiocgr','','','2022-10-09 13:32:51','2022-10-09 13:32:51','',0,'http://leoportfolio.local/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Limpieza_Auditorias_publicadas_2015-2020_sitioCGR.html',0,'attachment','text/html',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (74,1,'2022-10-09 13:34:55','2022-10-09 13:34:55','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As i show you in a last post, i used python with BeautifulSoup to download several of pdf files published in a government institution in order to make an analysis of this information. The scraping was the first part of the work, but then it was necessary to build the database. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To do that i used, again python, using its Pandas library. Here is the notebook:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<!--–– replace src and id. Note that the id appears in two places ––-->\n<iframe src=\"http://leoportfolio.local/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Resoluciones_auditorias_publicadas-2015-2020-part2.html\" id=\"DatasetPDF_published_CGR\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"100%\" frameborder=\"0\" style=\"border: 1px lightgrey solid;\">\n</iframe>\n<script>\n(function(){\n    var iframe = document.getElementById(\"DatasetPDF_published_CGR\");\n    function resize() {\n        iframe.style.height = \n        (iframe.contentWindow.document.body.scrollHeight + 4) + \'px\';\n        // \"body\" in the above line may need to be changed,\n        // depending on the specific version of Jupyter.\n        // For example, it may have to be replaced with \n        // .getElementById(\"notebook-container\"), and the \n        // DOM and the id may need to be manually added.\n    }\n    window.addEventListener(\"resize\", resize);\n    iframe.addEventListener(\"load\", resize);\n})()\n</script>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After building the dataset, and clean the first part, it was necessary to make a new job, that was check the similarity values in the \"institucion\" column. As was shown, this column has a lot of problems because some names are repeated with misspelling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A time ago, i found out that there is a tool develop by the open source community called <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://openrefine.org/\" target=\"_blank\">OpenRefine</a> and help to clean the messy data in a dataset. But in my case i wanted to do something with python and i also find out that there was a library called FuzzyWuzzy, that works similarly as OpenRefine. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What i understood from FuzzyWuzzy was that you need to have a list, series or whatever you want of the correct names that you want to change. Since a did not have this, i had to build it. And below is the work:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<!--–– replace src and id. Note that the id appears in two places ––-->\n<iframe src=\"http://leoportfolio.local/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Limpieza_Auditorias_publicadas_2015-2020_sitioCGR.html\" id=\"Limpieza_DatasetPDF_published_CGR\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"100%\" frameborder=\"0\" style=\"border: 1px lightgrey solid;\">\n</iframe>\n<script>\n(function(){\n    var iframe = document.getElementById(\"Limpieza_DatasetPDF_published_CGR\");\n    function resize() {\n        iframe.style.height = \n        (iframe.contentWindow.document.body.scrollHeight + 4) + \'px\';\n        // \"body\" in the above line may need to be changed,\n        // depending on the specific version of Jupyter.\n        // For example, it may have to be replaced with \n        // .getElementById(\"notebook-container\"), and the \n        // DOM and the id may need to be manually added.\n    }\n    window.addEventListener(\"resize\", resize);\n    iframe.addEventListener(\"load\", resize);\n})()\n</script>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The last phase of this project would be the analysis of the dataset, but this i will show you in this next post.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Building a dataset from published pdf files','','inherit','closed','closed','','68-revision-v1','','','2022-10-09 13:34:55','2022-10-09 13:34:55','',68,'http://leoportfolio.local/?p=74',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (75,1,'2022-10-09 13:36:59','2022-10-09 13:36:59','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As i show you in a last post, i used python with BeautifulSoup to download several of pdf files published in a government institution in order to make an analysis of this information. The scraping was the first part of the work, but then it was necessary to build the database. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To do that i used, again python, using its Pandas library. Here is the notebook:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<!--–– replace src and id. Note that the id appears in two places ––-->\n<iframe src=\"http://leoportfolio.local/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Resoluciones_auditorias_publicadas-2015-2020-part2.html\" id=\"DatasetPDF_published_CGR\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"100%\" frameborder=\"0\" style=\"border: 1px lightgrey solid;\">\n</iframe>\n<script>\n(function(){\n    var iframe = document.getElementById(\"DatasetPDF_published_CGR\");\n    function resize() {\n        iframe.style.height = \n        (iframe.contentWindow.document.body.scrollHeight + 4) + \'px\';\n        // \"body\" in the above line may need to be changed,\n        // depending on the specific version of Jupyter.\n        // For example, it may have to be replaced with \n        // .getElementById(\"notebook-container\"), and the \n        // DOM and the id may need to be manually added.\n    }\n    window.addEventListener(\"resize\", resize);\n    iframe.addEventListener(\"load\", resize);\n})()\n</script>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After building the dataset, and clean the first part, it was necessary to make a new job, that was check the similarity values in the \"institucion\" column. As was shown, this column has a lot of problems because some names are repeated with misspelling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A time ago, i found out that there is a tool develop by the open source community called <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://openrefine.org/\" target=\"_blank\">OpenRefine</a> and help to clean the messy data in a dataset. But in my case i wanted to do something with python and i also find out that there was a library called FuzzyWuzzy, that works similarly as OpenRefine. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What i understood from FuzzyWuzzy was that you need to have a list, series or whatever you want of the correct names that you want to change. Since a did not have this, i had to build it. And below is the work:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<!--–– replace src and id. Note that the id appears in two places ––-->\n<iframe src=\"http://leoportfolio.local/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Limpieza_Auditorias_publicadas_2015-2020_sitioCGR.html\" id=\"Limpieza_DatasetPDF_published_CGR\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"100%\" frameborder=\"0\" style=\"border: 1px lightgrey solid;\">\n</iframe>\n<script>\n(function(){\n    var iframe = document.getElementById(\"Limpieza_DatasetPDF_published_CGR\");\n    function resize() {\n        iframe.style.height = \n        (iframe.contentWindow.document.body.scrollHeight + 4) + \'px\';\n        // \"body\" in the above line may need to be changed,\n        // depending on the specific version of Jupyter.\n        // For example, it may have to be replaced with \n        // .getElementById(\"notebook-container\"), and the \n        // DOM and the id may need to be manually added.\n    }\n    window.addEventListener(\"resize\", resize);\n    iframe.addEventListener(\"load\", resize);\n})()\n</script>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The last phase of this project would be the analysis of the dataset, but this i will show you in this next post.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Building a dataset from published pdf files','','inherit','closed','closed','','68-autosave-v1','','','2022-10-09 13:36:59','2022-10-09 13:36:59','',68,'http://leoportfolio.local/?p=75',0,'revision','',0);
